Title:
RISC‑Y Business: Raging against the reduced machine

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post describes the engineering of a small, embeddable RISC‑V (rv64) virtual machine interpreter intended for low-footprint payload execution and practical obfuscation.  
- It avoids building a custom VM ISA by leveraging LLVM’s existing RISC‑V backend, then runs the guest bytecode inside a host process with a shared memory model (guest pointers are valid host pointers).  
- The authors build a freestanding toolchain (custom linker script, minimal CRT, relocation packing) to produce a raw binary blob that can be copied into memory and executed by the interpreter without RWX pages.  
- Hardening features include opcode enum shuffling, per-instruction XOR “encryption” keyed by bytecode offset, and a threaded interpreter using tail calls to increase indirect branching and complicate static analysis.  
- It also covers “whole-program LLVM” on Windows: embedding/extracting LTO bitcode from PE files, fixing alignment/padding issues, and retargeting x64 Windows LLVM IR to RISC‑V by generating import-resolving stubs that call back into the host.  
- Useful for red teamers, malware developers, and reverse engineers interested in VM-based obfuscation, payload staging, and LLVM-based transformation pipelines on Windows.

Technical Focus:
- RISC‑V rv64 interpreter design (register model, instruction decoding, dispatch)
- Freestanding binaries: custom linker scripts, CRT init arrays, relocation handling
- VM hardening: opcode shuffling, bytecode XOR transform, threaded interpreters (tail-call dispatch)
- Windows host integration: PEB walking, export resolution, host-call syscall bridge
- LLVM LTO bitcode embedding/extraction in PE and IR retargeting (x64 → riscv64)
- Build pipeline automation (CMake/clang-cl, lld, objcopy, Python post-processing)

Use Cases:
- Embed a compact VM to execute staged “business logic”/shellcode-like payloads without RWX memory
- Increase reverse-engineering cost via VM-based obfuscation (shuffled opcodes + encrypted bytecode + threaded dispatch)
- Generate polymorphic payload variants by recompiling/shuffling/encrypting bytecode
- Retarget and run simple Windows API-using C/C++ code inside a RISC‑V VM via LLVM IR rewriting
- Instrument/obfuscate/fuzz Windows programs by extracting embedded LLVM bitcode and post-processing it

Keywords:
RISC-V, rv64im, virtual machine interpreter, threaded interpreter, tail calls, musttail, opcode shuffling, bytecode encryption, XOR transform, LLVM, LTO, embedded bitcode, .llvmbc, clang-cl, lld, llvm-objcopy, PE, Windows PEB, export table walking, ntdll, syscall bridge, freestanding CRT, linker script, relocations, R_RISCV_64, IR retargeting, dllimport stubs, LoadLibraryA, MessageBoxA